Docker Architecture

Docker uses a client-server architecture where the Docker Client communicates with the Docker Daemon, which manages containers, images, networks, and volumes.

                   User
                     |
             docker run nginx
                     |
             +----------------+
             | Docker Client  |
             +----------------+
                     |
          Docker REST API (Unix Socket/TCP)
                     |
             +----------------+
             | Docker Daemon  | (dockerd)
             +----------------+
          /        |        \
         /         |         \
   Images     Containers   Networks
      |            |          |
      +------------+----------+
                   |
             containerd
                   |
                runc (OCI Runtime)
                   |
            Linux Kernel (Namespaces, Cgroups)
                   |
              Running Container
Docker Architecture Components
1. Docker Client (docker)
Command-line interface (CLI).
Sends commands to the Docker daemon.

Example:

docker run nginx
2. Docker Daemon (dockerd)
Core Docker service.
Builds images.
Creates and manages containers.
Manages networks and volumes.
Pulls images from registries.
3. Docker Registry

Stores Docker images.

Examples:

Docker Hub
Private Registry

Example:

docker pull nginx
4. Docker Images
Read-only templates.
Used to create containers.
Built using a Dockerfile.
5. Docker Containers
Running instances of images.
Isolated using Linux namespaces.
Resource-limited using cgroups.
6. containerd
Manages the complete lifecycle of containers.
Pulls images.
Creates snapshots.
Starts/stops containers.
7. runc
Low-level OCI runtime.
Creates the actual Linux container.
8. Linux Kernel

Provides container isolation through:

Namespaces (process, network, mount, PID isolation)
Cgroups (CPU, memory, I/O limits)
Union Filesystem (layered images)
What Happens When You Run docker run nginx?
docker run nginx
Step 1: User executes the command
User
  |
docker run nginx
Step 2: Docker Client receives the command

The Docker CLI parses the command and sends it to the Docker Daemon using the Docker API.

User
  |
Docker Client
Step 3: Docker Daemon checks for the image

It checks whether the nginx image already exists locally.

docker images
If present → Use it.
If not present → Pull it from the registry.
Step 4: Pull image (if needed)
Docker Daemon
      |
Docker Hub
      |
Download Image

Equivalent command:

docker pull nginx
Step 5: Create a writable container layer

Docker creates a new writable layer on top of the read-only image layers.

Image Layers (Read-only)
-------------------------
Layer 3
Layer 2
Layer 1
-------------------------
Writable Container Layer
Step 6: Create networking

Docker:

Assigns an IP address.
Connects the container to the default bridge network (unless another network is specified).
Step 7: Attach volumes (if specified)

If the command includes a volume:

docker run -v myvolume:/data nginx

Docker mounts myvolume into /data.

Step 8: Apply resource limits

If options are provided:

docker run --memory=512m --cpus=1 nginx

Docker configures Linux cgroups to enforce those limits.

Step 9: containerd prepares the container

containerd:

Creates the container metadata.
Prepares the filesystem snapshot.
Invokes the runtime.
Step 10: runc creates the container

runc:

Creates namespaces.
Sets up the filesystem.
Starts the container process.
Step 11: Start the main process

Docker executes the image's default CMD or ENTRYPOINT.

For the official Nginx image:

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

The Nginx server starts.

Step 12: Container is running

Check:

docker ps

Example:

CONTAINER ID   IMAGE   STATUS
abcd1234       nginx   Up 10 seconds
